  "prompt": "What are some cultural faux pas in Hungary?",
  "response": "Here are some cultural faux pas to avoid in Hungary:\n\n1. Drinking etiquette\n- Never clink beer glasses (this stems from historical Austrian oppression)\n- Always make eye contact and say \"Eg\u00e9szs\u00e9gedre\" when toasting\n\n2. Social interactions\n- Don't be overly loud or boisterous in public\n- Avoid discussing sensitive historical topics like the Communist era without sensitivity\n- Don't assume Hungarians are part of Slavic cultures (they're very distinct)\n\n3. Dining customs\n- Don't start eating before the host\n- Keep hands visible at the table, not in your lap\n- Tipping is expected (10-15% in restaurants)\n\n4. Communication\n- Avoid addressing people by first name unless invited\n- Use formal language (maga) with strangers and older people\n- Don't be too direct or blunt in conversations\n\n5. General etiquette\n- Remove shoes when entering someone's home\n- Hungarians value punctuality\n- Don't discuss personal income or financial matters openly\n- Avoid excessive public displays of affection\n\n6. Gift-giving\n- Bring an odd number of flowers (even numbers are for funerals)\n- Avoid giving chrysanthemums (associated with funerals)\n\nUnderstanding these nuances can help show respect for Hungarian culture.",
